

### 1. `alert()` Popup

The `alert()` method displays a simple message in a popup box. It is commonly used to show information or warning messages.

```javascript
alert("This is an alert box!");
```

- **Example Explanation**: When this code is executed, a popup box with the message "This is an alert box!" will appear. The user can only close the popup by clicking the "OK" button.

### 2. `confirm()` Popup

The `confirm()` method displays a message in a popup box with "OK" and "Cancel" buttons. It is often used to confirm a user's action.

```javascript
let userConfirmation = confirm("Do you want to proceed?");
if (userConfirmation) {
    console.log("User clicked OK.");
} else {
    console.log("User clicked Cancel.");
}
```

- **Example Explanation**: This code will display a confirmation popup asking "Do you want to proceed?". If the user clicks "OK", the `userConfirmation` variable will be `true`, and "User clicked OK." will be logged to the console. If the user clicks "Cancel", the variable will be `false`, and "User clicked Cancel." will be logged.

### 3. `prompt()` Popup

The `prompt()` method displays a popup box that prompts the user to enter some text. It also has "OK" and "Cancel" buttons.

```javascript
let userInput = prompt("Please enter your name:", "John Doe");
if (userInput !== null) {
    console.log("Hello, " + userInput + "!");
} else {
    console.log("User cancelled the prompt.");
}
```
